After everything seemed to have settled down a bit, I thought it’d be fun to do a cursory analysis of the winners of the six current World Marathon Majors.

What are the World Marathon Majors?

The World Marathon Majors is a collection of six annual marathons: Tokyo, New York, Boston, London, Berlin, Chicago. And in the requisite??? years, includes the World Championship (held every 2 years by the IAAF) and the Olympic Marathon. The races are run as a series and the male and female athlete who score the most points from the qualifying races are crowned the champions of the series (defined as the points from a max of two of the qualifying races). For us non-elites, we can quality as a Six Star Finisher, wherein after successfully completing all six of the World Marathon Majors, would recieve an official certificate and Six Star Finisher Medal.

EDA

After scraping Wikipedia for the past winners of the races and cleaning up the data, I had a nice data file consisting of, for each race, the marathon, the winner, the year, the winner’s gender, and the winner’s time. A quick first plot to look at could be the count of WMM wins by country.

The common knowledge that Eastern Africa (i.e. Kenya and Ethiopa) are dominanting distance running is clearly displayed in the plot, followed by the United States, Germany, and the UK. It’s pretty easy to see why, after Kenya and Ethiopia, these three countires have the most victores, as five of the six marathons tkae place in these countires. But when did this domination by the East Africans begin?

But, before leaving this chart completely, we can note that German and UK wins started picking up soon after first couple of their respective marathons (chicago = 1977, berlin = 1974, london = 1981, ).
